issue.title: layer pack/unpack: unify on-disk format configuration
issue.body: Currently we have two different systems for configuring the on-disk format for packing (`TranslateOverlayWhiteouts`) and unpacking (`WhiteoutMode`), but ideally it would be a single configuration type with per-format configuration (in the case of overlayfs this would be whether to use userxattr -- see #576).

pull_request.title: Configure Mend Bolt for GitHub
pull_request.body:
Welcome to [Mend Bolt for GitHub](https://github.com/apps/mend-bolt-for-github) (formerly WhiteSource). This is an onboarding PR to help you understand and configure settings before Mend starts scanning your repository for security vulnerabilities.

:vertical_traffic_light: Mend Bolt for GitHub will start scanning your repository only once you merge this Pull Request. To disable Mend Bolt for GitHub, simply close this Pull Request. 



---

### What to Expect

This PR contains a '.whitesource' configuration file which can be customized to your needs. If no changes were applied to this file, Mend Bolt for GitHub will use the default configuration.

Before merging this PR, Make sure the [Issues tab is enabled](https://docs.mend.io/bundle/community_tools/page/enabling_the__issues__tab_for_the_github_repository.html). Once you merge this PR, Mend Bolt for GitHub will scan your repository and create a GitHub Issue for every vulnerability detected in your repository. 

If you do not want a GitHub Issue to be created for each detected vulnerability, you can edit the '.whitesource' file and set the 'minSeverityLevel' parameter to 'NONE'. 

---

:question: Got questions? Check out Mend Bolt for GitHub [docs](https://docs.mend.io/bundle/community_tools/page/mend_bolt_for_github.html).

pull_request.title: draft: issue-10: POC git based recipe versioning app
pull_request.body:
This POC, demonstrates git based functionality for a recipe management system. You can do the following:
1. Create new recipes
2. Update existing recipes
3. View the version history of recipes
4. Select a previous version of a recipe to be at the head of the version history
5. Fork from a `test_user`'s list of recipes

To start the development servers:
 ```bash
 # Start the backend server (in one terminal)
./start-dev.sh
 cd backend
 npm run dev
 
 # Start the frontend dev server (in another terminal)
 docker exec -it gitgrub-dev bash
cd frontend
 npm run dev
 ```

Access the app in your local browser at:
   - Frontend: `http://localhost:5173`
   - Backend API: `http://localhost:3001`

## How to Test the Forking Functionality

1. **Start the application**
6. **Navigate to test_user's recipes**:
   - Go to `http://localhost:5173/users/test_user/recipes`
   - You should see the sample recipes (Chocolate Cake, Banana Bread)
   
7. **View a recipe**:
   - Click on one of the recipes to view it
   - You should see a "Fork Recipe" button since you're viewing as 'demo' but the recipe belongs to 'test_user'
   
8. **Fork the recipe**:
   - Click the "Fork Recipe" button
   - You'll be redirected to your newly forked recipe under the 'demo' user (You should see this reflected in URL)
   
9. **Verify fork information**:
   - The forked recipe should show a "Forked from test_user's recipe" message with a link
   - Click that link to go back to the original recipe
   
10. **View your recipes**:
   - Go to `http://localhost:5173/users/demo/recipes`
   - You should see the forked recipe in your recipe list

issue.title: 03 Naming accounts consistently
issue.body:
### Link to the coursework

Your own accounts!

### Why are we doing this?

## Naming Accounts Consistently
>[!TIP]
> Use the same name everywhere in your work with CYF.

### Consistency in online account names
During the CYF course you will make accounts online. (Such as Slack, GitHub, Google, LinkedIn...)

You should always use your **real name**. It must always be the **same name.** Don't use any other words apart from your name. Do not ever put your birth year or age in your user name. These things can harm your job prospects so start as you mean to go on.

Trainees use the same name everywhere in their work with CYF. 

>[!NOTE]
> CYF recognises you may need to keep your birth name private.  When we say real name, we mean the name **you go by.** It does not have to match your birth certificate or any other legal document.  

Your profile picture does not have to be a picture of you. It must be safe for work, consistent and unique, so you don't get mixed up with other people. If you need to keep your photo private, you can use [Robohash](https://robohash.org/) to make a unique profile picture.

## Summary
Don't use cute handles or put the year of your birth in your username.

Use the same username and picture across all CYF accounts. This also means professional profiles like Linkedin and GitHub.

### Maximum time in hours

.1

### How to get help

Swap with a classmate and check their profile. Ask yourself:

If you didn't know them, would you know this was their Slack account? If you didn't know them, would you know this was their LInkedIn? If you were a recruiter reading their GitHub, could you find their LinkedIn within six seconds? If you wanted to invite them to an opportunity, could you do that without asking them first?
